SIMPLE: equimomental
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Equimomental
<hw>E`qui*mo*men"tal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[<ets>Equi-</ets> + <ets>momental</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Mech.)</fld>
<def>Having equal moments of inertia.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Two bodies or systems of bodies are said to be
<xex>equimomental</xex> when their moments of inertia about all straight
lines are equal each to each.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Equimomental cone of a given rigid body</b></col>, <cd>a
conical surface that has any given vertex, and is described by a
straight line which moves in such manner that the moment of inertia of
the given rigid body about the line is in all its positions the
same.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Equimultiple</ent>⟦br⟧
